'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">public sector research establishments (PSREs)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research Councils UK is a strategic partnership set up to champion research supported by the seven UK Research Councils.  RCUK was estab</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lished in 2002 to enable the Councils to work together more effectively to enhance the overall impact and effectiveness of their research, training and innovation activities, contributing to the delivery of the Government’s objectives for science and innov</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ation.  Further details are available at </span><a href="http://www.rcuk.ac.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.rcuk.ac.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This evidence is submitted by RCUK and represents its independent views.  It does not include, or necessarily reflect the views of the Knowledge and Innovati</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">on Group in the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS).  The submission is made on behalf of the following Councils</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Arts and Humanities Research Council (AHRC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council (BBSRC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Engineering and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Medical Research Council (MRC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Natural Environment Research Council (NERC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Science and Technology Facilities Council (STFC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This evidence responds to the first question</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">suggestions </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for future inquires on UK R&amp;D funding’. RCUK does not have any further comments on the other areas of investigation at this time i.e. the NAO review of R&amp;D funding, the 2010 and 2013 spending reviews </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> PSREs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Suggestions for future </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">inquiries on UK R&amp;D funding:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> impact on the research base of continued “flat cash funding”. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The committee has regularly prioritised examination of spending reviews and overall effects on the science base.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The maintenance of existing (non-indexed) fund</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ing levels for the ring-fenced Science budget was very welcome amidst wider UK government cuts. However there is still the potential for significant impact on the research base with the effective cut of over </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">30-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">40% </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in the budget over the spending review </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">period. This has the potential to be exacerbated with the current SR15/16 settlements. A review of the long-term impact of budget decisions on the wider research base and any communities in particular would be welcome.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ownership and funding of Public Sect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or Research Establishments (PSREs). </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">PSREs are a diverse collection of public bodies carrying out important research. This research supports a wide range of Government objectives, including informing Government policy making, statutory and regulatory functi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ons and providing a national strategic resource in key areas of scientific research. In many cases past reviews have been dealing with historical legacies from a particular PSRE and not taking a forwards look at their wider role and benefits to the researc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">h base. There is a better need to understand the role PSREs play in ensuring the UK has a diverse and responsive science base, including: how they are created, reviewed, renewed and rationalised; how new national needs are identified and translated into PS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">REs where appropriate; governance and ownership models; and the role of Government Departments and of Research Councils in all of the above.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The contribution of the research base to the economy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. It is often a challenge for the research base to articulate </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the specific benefits of public funding of research, outside a few well documented case studies. Any reports attempting to quantify the benefits have acknowledged they are significant and generally under estimated. Though most have struggled to extend thei</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r methodology outside the specific sector of interest. Given the important role innovation has in economic growth, further discussion of this issue is important to ensure the research base if appropriately valued. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UK position in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bioeconomy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. There are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a number of key research and technology led areas of the economy that will be vital for stimulating the economy and generating growth. The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bioeconomy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> represent major new bio-based industries (growth and jobs) yet there is a sense in the UK that we have no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t really grasped the true potential compared to some economic competitors (USA recently published a major </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bioeconomy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> blueprint (strategy) and Germany and other nations have similar unified strategies). The UK has no single strategy of coordinated approach,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> despite being the world leader academically in many biosciences disciplines.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> An enquiry could helpfully flag the importance of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bioeconomy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to UK growth and the need for the UK to better position itself to address this key economic sector.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Incentivisi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ng UK companies to invest in R&amp;D. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are many mechanisms used globally to incentivise companies to invest in R&amp;D, especially in partnership with researchers. How suitable these mechanisms are to the UK situation, or whether there are other ways to incen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tivise UK companies to invest, is an area worthy of further exploration. It would also be of interest to explore some of the barriers to some of these schemes such as restrictions placed on RCs in funding companies or charities directly.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">High-level skills</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. There are currently significant changes in the higher education in terms of funding and the long-term effects of the changes to the undergraduate fees structure. There are significant concerns about the knock-on effect these changes might have on the pos</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t-graduate training which underpins the future UK skills base. In addition to these changes there are also positive developments in how doctoral training is evolving (e.g. via DTPs), and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">new skills opportunities at postdoctoral research level. There are al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">so concerns around supporting high-level skills and development of future research expertise across the breadth of subjects required to underpin economic growth and future prosperity.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>